The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       The City Diary
                The Christian community in the state will organise a three-day relay fast to protest the attacks on Christians in Orissa, Karnataka and other parts of the country and the murder of Swami Lakshmananda by suspected Maoists. Led by the bishops of various churches, the relay fast will be held in the Metro channel from 9am on Friday. Over 500 people are expected to take part in the fast and a human chain will be formed for 10 minutes after the fast ends on Sunday afternoon.     An assistant commissioner of the central excise department (region- V), A.K. Pattanayak, was arrested by the CBI in Rajdanga on Wednesday while allegedly accepting a bribe of Rs 1 lakh from a copper factory owner in South 24-Parganas to regularise his records. CBI officials said Pattanayak, 53, had asked the owner to bring the money near a hospital in Rajdanga. The owner informed CBI sleuths, who laid a trap.    A city sessions court on Wednesday rejected the bail plea of Syed Mohiuddin, alias Pappu, in the Rizwanur Rahman death case. The court extended his jail custody till November 20.    Power supply may be affected in Badartala and Bagdipara Road areas, on the southern fringes of the city, on November 14 and 15 from 8am to 5pm as CESC will upgrade the high voltage network from 6KV to 11KV.     Manjit Singh Bist, 40, was found dead in his Behala home late on Tuesday. Bist worked in an eatery on Park Street and lived with his wife and two children in a rented flat, police said. After having dinner on Tuesday, his wife stepped out of the house for a few minutes. When she returned, she found him lying unconscious on the floor. He was taken to hospital, where he was declared dead.    The Jain Samaj has announced a Rs 1-lakh award for information leading to the recovery of the idol of Lord Pareshnath that was stolen from the Pareshnath Digambar Jain Temple at Alipore Park Place on October 8. Any person with information can contact temple trustee Bhagchand Kashliwal at 9831002729.                                                                                                                                                              
